


03-21-2023 - Arrays Part 3


Arrays:
-Collection of datas - elements
-Arrays allow duplicates
-Arrays are fixed sized. You CANNOT add or delete elements, you CANNOT change the size.
-It allows you to update, search, retrieve, sort elements in an array
	sorting numbers -> smallest to largest
	sorting strings -> lexicographically
-You can iterate arrays with for, for each, while, do-while loop
-Default values of different data types of arrays
	-byte, short, int, long -> 0
	-float, double -> 0.0
	-boolean -> false
	-Objects -> null

-To be able to print the elements stored in an array, you will need to Arrays.toString(arrayVariable) method




String methods that returns Arrays

1. toCharArray()
TASK: it converts the String to char[] array.
-this method is non-static
-this method is a return type and it returns an char[] array
-It does not take any argument
	

	EXAMPLE:

	String name = "John";

	char[] charsOfName = name.toCharArray(); // ACCEPTABLE

	System.out.println(Arrays.toString(charsOfName)); // [J, o, h, n]



2. split()
TASK: it splits the string from the given argument and
-this is a non-static method
-return and it returns String[] array
-it takes an argument

EXAMPLE:
	String str = "Hello World";
	str.split(" "); // "Hello", "World"

	String str2 = "Today is a nice class";
	str2.split(" "); // "Today", "is", "a", "nice", "class"

	String str3 = "John | Doe | 11/11/1999 | johndoe@gmail.com | Chicago";
	str3.split(" | "); // "John", "Doe"

 	String str3 = "Hello   World";
 	["Hello", "", "", "World"] ->

arr.length - emptyOnes -> 2


3, 3, 5, 6, 8, 10


